Research indicates that the effectiveness of punishment in deterring crime is limited. Increasing the severity of penalties, such as imposing longer prison sentences, has minimal impact on reducing crime rates. This is partly because many individuals are unaware of the specific legal sanctions for various offenses. Moreover, harsher punishments can sometimes have the opposite effect, potentially increasing recidivism by exposing offenders to environments where they may learn more effective criminal strategies. ([unsw.edu.au](https://www.unsw.edu.au/news/2020/07/do-harsher-punishments-deter-crime-?utm_source=openai))

In contrast, enhancing the certainty of apprehension has been found to be a more effective deterrent. When individuals perceive a higher likelihood of being caught, they are more likely to refrain from engaging in criminal activities. This suggests that strategies focusing on increasing the probability of detection, such as improved policing and surveillance, may be more successful in preventing crime than those emphasizing harsher penalties. ([gigafact.org](https://gigafact.org/fact-briefs/does-increasing-the-penalties-for-a-crime-reduce-the-incidence-of-that-crime/?utm_source=openai))

Additionally, some studies suggest that the frequency of enforcement plays a more significant role in reducing violations than the severity of punishment. Consistent and predictable enforcement can deter individuals from committing offenses, as the perceived risk of being caught increases. ([pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8545445/?utm_source=openai))

In summary, while punishment serves as a component of the criminal justice system, its deterrent effect is more closely associated with the certainty and frequency of enforcement rather than the severity of the penalties imposed. 

